data.description: Rutgers Sikh Kirtan Night is a serene and uplifting evening hosted by the Sikh Student Association that brings the campus community together through the soulful singing of shabad kirtan, devotional hymns from the Guru Granth Sahib accompanied by traditional instruments like the harmonium and tabla. The event fosters an atmosphere of peace, reflection, and unity, allowing students and guests to de-stress while connecting spiritually. True to Sikh tradition, the night also includes Langar, a free communal meal that symbolizes equality and service. In addition, some gatherings feature cultural elements such as turban tying and interactive activities, making the event both spiritually enriching and culturally engaging. Open to people of all backgrounds, Kirtan Night offers a welcoming space to experience Sikh faith, music, and community on campus.
data.name: Rutgers Sikh Kirtan Night

Kick off our Fall 2025 series with a beginner-friendly crafting session focused on cartoon-style self-portraits, vision boarding, and expressing yourself through drawing, collage, and mixed media! Artsy door prizes! Bring a friend! Taught by a Scarlet Arts Rx student teaching artist from Rutgers Mason Gross School of the Arts. Foundational art skills you will learn at this event: Cutting interesting shapes, Collage / mood boarding, and Cartoon self-portraits (out of the paper shapes). Free supplies, snacks, and boba provided! Supplies are limited – First come, first served. All skill levels and walk-ins welcome! This experience counts towards the Douglass Discovery curriculum requirement. R3: Career/Discovery/Professional Development/Research.Reminder: To receive DRC curriculum credit, you must complete a reflection survey.

data.description: Join the BOLD Center at Douglass as we host our annual career conference! The Christiana Foglio DC'84 Douglass Career Conference is designed to empower students through career planning, discuss topics related to the workforce, and meet other professionals in a variety of industries to share their wealth of knowledge. Learn tips and tools for starting your career, how to navigate networking and interviewing, and the best ways to make your mark in the workplace. With a special focus on doing good work, we will also be hosting a packing party at the conference this year to donate items to community partners in need.  There will be food, giveaways, prizes, and networking opportunities.
data.name: Christiana Foglio DC'84 Douglass Career Conference

data.description: Stop by Douglass Library to experience a solo exhibition of artwork by the 2025-2026 Lebowitz Artist-in-Residence, Liz Collins, on view September 2 through March 13! Collins is a Brooklyn based artist that works across art and design. She is known for her innovative multimedia fabric, knitwear, and textile work, along with the fashion label she created. Don't miss out—RSVP today and join the Center for Women in the Arts at Douglass to view the exhibition during a reception and for a talk by artist Liz Collins on October 16, from 5:00 to 6:30 PM! All are welcome!Schedule: 5:00-5:30pm exhibition viewing & reception (light refreshments served); 5:30-6:30pm artist’s talk. This experience counts towards the Douglass Discovery curriculum requirement. R3: Career/Discovery/Professional Development/Research.Reminder: To receive DRC curriculum credit, you must complete a reflection survey.

data.description: Join us for our annual 5K Run and Mile Walk! Whether you run, walk, volunteer, or cheer from the sidelines, help us raise awareness and support the fight against lung cancer. All proceeds are donated to Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center to support lung cancer research efforts. Interested in walking or running? Register here on our website!   Interested in volunteering? Join our GroupMe!   The first 200 participants (walker or runner) will receive a free Wawa hot beverage coupon upon check-in! The first 50 early 5K registrants will receive a free t-shirt! Food, beverages, raffles, and games will be included!
